[2026-07-17] [Ask My Docs / Observability] — Finding (HIGH), fixed same session: the first real Langfuse Cloud trace (Block 9, Chunk 9.0) revealed that Block 7's spans never actually nested into one trace per query -- each of the 6 spans (bm25/vector/fusion/rerank/generate/verify) landed as its own separate root trace. Root cause: Langfuse/OTel nesting requires a child span to open while a parent span's context is active; sharing one ObservabilityContext/tracer instance (Block 7 Decision 6) was necessary but not sufficient, since neither answer_with_verified_citations nor answer_question ever opened a wrapping span of their own. Invisible to Block 7's own unit tests (SpyTracer only asserted span names/counts, never enter/exit nesting order against a real backend). Same bug shape found and fixed in eval/pipeline.py's _evaluate_one (5 spans, no wrapper) in the same pass, per user's explicit choice to fix both together rather than defer the eval-path twin.
[2026-07-17] [Ask My Docs / Observability] — Decision (Block 9, Chunk 9.0 fix): answer_with_verified_citations wraps its whole call chain in one `query.answer_with_verified_citations` span; eval/pipeline.py's _evaluate_one wraps its whole per-question call chain in one `eval.question.<id>` span (dynamic name per question, for dashboard readability). Regression coverage added structurally (not via a real backend) by extending the shared spy_tracer fixture (tests/conftest.py) to record enter/exit order -- a missing wrapping `with` block is now catchable by a fast unit test, not just a real-infrastructure spot-check.
[2026-07-18] [Ask My Docs / Portfolio] — Finding, not a decision: Block 9's planned regression demo (config.yaml rerank.enabled: false, real eval --retrieval-only run) did not reproduce a regression -- it measurably improved every retrieval metric (mean_recall_at_k 0.616->0.669, mean_ndcg 0.783->0.830), all PASS against the real baseline. retrieval.top_n: 20->3 degraded all three metrics but stayed within eval.tolerance (0.1), still PASS. retrieval.top_n: 20->1 produced a real, reproducible gate failure (mean_recall_at_k 0.356 FAIL, mean_ndcg 0.478 FAIL, mean_mrr 0.875 PASS, exit code 1), confirmed stable across two runs, then reverted cleanly. Used as the eval report's real regression example instead of the originally planned config change.
[2026-07-18] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Decision (post-Block-9): pin generation.temperature to 0.0 (GenerationConfig, new field, default 0.0), wired into generate_answer's messages.parse() call, matching the pattern already used for citations.judge_temperature/eval.judge_temperature. Because: generation non-determinism was evidenced three separate times (Block 6's original q1 VMC/VSO finding, plus a second live instance during Block 9's own README-capture run) and directly undermines the eval-gated-CI portfolio claim -- a hiring-manager-facing system whose demo answers vary run-to-run, and whose eval gate can't distinguish real regressions from generation noise, is a weaker proof point than one with reproducible output. Trades whatever quality benefit default sampling provided for reproducibility.
[2026-07-18] [Ask My Docs / Generation] — Correction to the immediately preceding decisions.log entry: pinning generation.temperature=0.0 was shipped verified only against fake-client unit tests, not the real API, and broke every real query -- claude-sonnet-5 returns a real 400 BadRequestError, "temperature is deprecated for this model." A follow-up probe found top_p and top_k are deprecated for this model too (same error shape for both). Reverted the field and the API call entirely. This model currently exposes no manual sampling-determinism control -- the eval harness's tolerance-band comparison design (not a hard cutoff) is the real, load-bearing mitigation for generation non-determinism, not a stopgap pending a temperature fix. Root cause of the mistake: skipped the exact "verify third-party API behavior with a real probe before shipping" rule this project's own build.md states, on the wrong assumption that temperature was safe to reuse because citations.judge_temperature/eval.judge_temperature already worked -- those target claude-haiku-4-5-20251001, a different model, and model-specific parameter support was never checked.
